### LLVM&#95;ABI&#95;NOT&#95;EXPORTED {#afdd270405f597b9e732c56397ef25888}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>#define LLVM&#95;ABI&#95;NOT&#95;EXPORTED</>}>
LLVM&#95;ABI is the main export/visibility macro to mark something as explicitly exported when llvm is built as a shared library with everything else that is unannotated will have internal visibility.

LLVM&#95;ABI&#95;EXPORT is for the special case for things like plugin symbol declarations or definitions where we don&#39;t want the macro to be switching between dllexport and dllimport on windows based on what codebase is being built, it will only be dllexport. For non windows platforms this macro behaves the same as LLVM&#95;ABI.

LLVM&#95;EXPORT&#95;TEMPLATE is used on explicit template instantiations in source files that were declared extern in a header. This macro is only set as a compiler export attribute on windows, on other platforms it does nothing.

LLVM&#95;TEMPLATE&#95;ABI is for annotating extern template declarations in headers for both functions and classes. On windows its turned in to dllimport for library consumers, for other platforms its a default visibility attribute.

LLVM&#95;C&#95;ABI is used to annotated functions and data that need to be exported for the libllvm-c API. This used both for the llvm-c headers and for the functions declared in the different Target&#39;s c++ source files that don&#39;t include the header forward declaring them.

Definition at line <a href="#l00177">177</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/compiler-h">Compiler.h</a>.
</MemberDefinition>

<MemberDefinition

LLVM&#95;LIBRARY&#95;VISIBILITY - If a class marked with this attribute is linked into a shared library, then the class should be private to the library and not accessible from outside it.

Can also be used to mark variables and functions, making them private to any shared library they are linked into. On PE/COFF targets, library visibility is the default, so this isn&#39;t needed.

LLVM&#95;EXTERNAL&#95;VISIBILITY - classes, functions, and variables marked with this attribute will be made public and visible outside of any shared library they are linked in to.

### LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL {#a793005af6ae802d5a2a2e8ceb4ac2135}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>#define LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL</>}>
\\macro LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL A thread-local storage specifier which can be used with globals, extern globals, and static globals.

This is essentially an extremely restricted analog to C++11&#39;s thread&#95;local support. It uses thread&#95;local if available, falling back on gcc &#95;&#95;thread if not. &#95;&#95;thread doesn&#39;t support many of the C++11 thread&#95;local&#39;s features. You should only use this for PODs that you can statically initialize to some constant value. In almost all circumstances this is most appropriate for use with a pointer, integer, or small aggregation of pointers and integers.

Definition at line <a href="#l00662">662</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/include/include/llvm/include/llvm/support/compiler-h">Compiler.h</a>.

<Link id="l00270" /><CodeLine lineNumber="270"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00271" /><CodeLine lineNumber="271"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Some compilers warn about unused functions. When a function is sometimes</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00272" /><CodeLine lineNumber="272"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// used or not depending on build settings (e.g. a function only called from</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00273" /><CodeLine lineNumber="273"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// within &quot;assert&quot;), this attribute can be used to suppress such warnings.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00274" /><CodeLine lineNumber="274"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00275" /><CodeLine lineNumber="275"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// However, it shouldn&#39;t be used for unused &#42;variables&#42;, as those have a much</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00276" /><CodeLine lineNumber="276"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// more portable solution:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00277" /><CodeLine lineNumber="277"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">//   (void)unused&#95;var&#95;name;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00278" /><CodeLine lineNumber="278"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Prefer cast-to-void wherever it is sufficient.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00279" /><CodeLine lineNumber="279"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#if &#95;&#95;has&#95;attribute(unused)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00280" /><CodeLine lineNumber="280"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;ATTRIBUTE&#95;UNUSED &#95;&#95;attribute&#95;&#95;((&#95;&#95;unused&#95;&#95;))</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00588" /><CodeLine lineNumber="588"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// infer an arc from the begin to the end when they share the same pointer</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00589" /><CodeLine lineNumber="589"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// argument.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00590" /><CodeLine lineNumber="590"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanHappensBefore(cv) AnnotateHappensBefore(&#95;&#95;FILE&#95;&#95;, &#95;&#95;LINE&#95;&#95;, cv)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00591" /><CodeLine lineNumber="591"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00592" /><CodeLine lineNumber="592"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// This marker defines the destination of a happens-before arc.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00593" /><CodeLine lineNumber="593"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanHappensAfter(cv) AnnotateHappensAfter(&#95;&#95;FILE&#95;&#95;, &#95;&#95;LINE&#95;&#95;, cv)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00594" /><CodeLine lineNumber="594"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00595" /><CodeLine lineNumber="595"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Ignore any races on writes between here and the next TsanIgnoreWritesEnd.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00596" /><CodeLine lineNumber="596"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanIgnoreWritesBegin() AnnotateIgnoreWritesBegin(&#95;&#95;FILE&#95;&#95;, &#95;&#95;LINE&#95;&#95;)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00597" /><CodeLine lineNumber="597"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00598" /><CodeLine lineNumber="598"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Resume checking for racy writes.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00599" /><CodeLine lineNumber="599"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanIgnoreWritesEnd() AnnotateIgnoreWritesEnd(&#95;&#95;FILE&#95;&#95;, &#95;&#95;LINE&#95;&#95;)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00600" /><CodeLine lineNumber="600"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#else</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00601" /><CodeLine lineNumber="601" lineLink="#a186eadfc2c525b71adaf35e7487eccac"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanHappensBefore(cv)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00602" /><CodeLine lineNumber="602" lineLink="#a4a8a06812caf14bdec3b541b578b8344"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanHappensAfter(cv)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00603" /><CodeLine lineNumber="603" lineLink="#ae7ae7168870d6f719670bf0f47b9ade5"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanIgnoreWritesBegin()</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00604" /><CodeLine lineNumber="604" lineLink="#a6d95fe36240cded45e8889c2491a78f5"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor"># define TsanIgnoreWritesEnd()</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00605" /><CodeLine lineNumber="605"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#endif</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00606" /><CodeLine lineNumber="606"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00607" /><CodeLine lineNumber="607"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// \\macro LLVM&#95;NO&#95;SANITIZE</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00608" /><CodeLine lineNumber="608"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Disable a particular sanitizer for a function.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00609" /><CodeLine lineNumber="609"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#if &#95;&#95;has&#95;attribute(no&#95;sanitize)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00610" /><CodeLine lineNumber="610"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;NO&#95;SANITIZE(KIND) &#95;&#95;attribute&#95;&#95;((no&#95;sanitize(KIND)))</span></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00613" /><CodeLine lineNumber="613"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#endif</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00614" /><CodeLine lineNumber="614"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00615" /><CodeLine lineNumber="615"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Mark debug helper function definitions like dump() that should not be</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00616" /><CodeLine lineNumber="616"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// stripped from debug builds.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00617" /><CodeLine lineNumber="617"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Note that you should also surround dump() functions with</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00618" /><CodeLine lineNumber="618"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// &#96;#if !defined(NDEBUG) || defined(LLVM&#95;ENABLE&#95;DUMP)&#96; so they do always</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00619" /><CodeLine lineNumber="619"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// get stripped in release builds.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00620" /><CodeLine lineNumber="620"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// FIXME: Move this to a private config.h as it&#39;s not usable in public headers.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00621" /><CodeLine lineNumber="621"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#if !defined(NDEBUG) || defined(LLVM&#95;ENABLE&#95;DUMP)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00622" /><CodeLine lineNumber="622" lineLink="#aa863693eef567397d9c292da5bf22d34"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;DUMP&#95;METHOD LLVM&#95;ATTRIBUTE&#95;NOINLINE LLVM&#95;ATTRIBUTE&#95;USED</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00623" /><CodeLine lineNumber="623"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#else</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00624" /><CodeLine lineNumber="624"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;DUMP&#95;METHOD LLVM&#95;ATTRIBUTE&#95;NOINLINE</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00625" /><CodeLine lineNumber="625"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#endif</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00626" /><CodeLine lineNumber="626"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00627" /><CodeLine lineNumber="627"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// \\macro LLVM&#95;PRETTY&#95;FUNCTION</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00628" /><CodeLine lineNumber="628"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// Gets a user-friendly looking function signature for the current scope</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00629" /><CodeLine lineNumber="629"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// using the best available method on each platform.  The exact format of the</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00630" /><CodeLine lineNumber="630"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// resulting string is implementation specific and non-portable, so this should</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00631" /><CodeLine lineNumber="631"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// only be used, for example, for logging or diagnostics.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00632" /><CodeLine lineNumber="632"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#if defined(&#95;MSC&#95;VER)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00633" /><CodeLine lineNumber="633"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;PRETTY&#95;FUNCTION &#95;&#95;FUNCSIG&#95;&#95;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00634" /><CodeLine lineNumber="634"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#elif defined(&#95;&#95;GNUC&#95;&#95;) || defined(&#95;&#95;clang&#95;&#95;)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00635" /><CodeLine lineNumber="635"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;PRETTY&#95;FUNCTION &#95;&#95;PRETTY&#95;FUNCTION&#95;&#95;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00636" /><CodeLine lineNumber="636"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#else</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00637" /><CodeLine lineNumber="637" lineLink="#add3e64f9d3d35dff1307ced174a44b29"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;PRETTY&#95;FUNCTION &#95;&#95;func&#95;&#95;</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00638" /><CodeLine lineNumber="638"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#endif</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00639" /><CodeLine lineNumber="639"></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00640" /><CodeLine lineNumber="640"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// \\macro LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00641" /><CodeLine lineNumber="641"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// A thread-local storage specifier which can be used with globals,</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00642" /><CodeLine lineNumber="642"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// extern globals, and static globals.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00643" /><CodeLine lineNumber="643"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">///</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00644" /><CodeLine lineNumber="644"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// This is essentially an extremely restricted analog to C++11&#39;s thread&#95;local</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00645" /><CodeLine lineNumber="645"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// support. It uses thread&#95;local if available, falling back on gcc &#95;&#95;thread</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00646" /><CodeLine lineNumber="646"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// if not. &#95;&#95;thread doesn&#39;t support many of the C++11 thread&#95;local&#39;s</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00647" /><CodeLine lineNumber="647"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// features. You should only use this for PODs that you can statically</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00648" /><CodeLine lineNumber="648"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// initialize to some constant value. In almost all circumstances this is most</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00649" /><CodeLine lineNumber="649"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// appropriate for use with a pointer, integer, or small aggregation of</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00650" /><CodeLine lineNumber="650"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">/// pointers and integers.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00651" /><CodeLine lineNumber="651"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#if LLVM&#95;ENABLE&#95;THREADS</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00652" /><CodeLine lineNumber="652"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#if &#95;&#95;has&#95;feature(cxx&#95;thread&#95;local) || defined(&#95;MSC&#95;VER)</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00653" /><CodeLine lineNumber="653"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL thread&#95;local</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#else</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00655" /><CodeLine lineNumber="655"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// Clang, GCC, and other compatible compilers used &#95;&#95;thread prior to C++11 and</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00656" /><CodeLine lineNumber="656"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// we only need the restricted functionality that provides.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00657" /><CodeLine lineNumber="657"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL &#95;&#95;thread</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00658" /><CodeLine lineNumber="658"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#endif</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00659" /><CodeLine lineNumber="659"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#else </span><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// !LLVM&#95;ENABLE&#95;THREADS</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00660" /><CodeLine lineNumber="660"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// If threading is disabled entirely, this compiles to nothing and you get</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00661" /><CodeLine lineNumber="661"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">// a normal global variable.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00662" /><CodeLine lineNumber="662" lineLink="#a793005af6ae802d5a2a2e8ceb4ac2135"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#define LLVM&#95;THREAD&#95;LOCAL</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00663" /><CodeLine lineNumber="663"><span class="doxyHighlightPreprocessor">#endif</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00664" /><CodeLine lineNumber="664"></CodeLine>
